      <hedline>
        <hl1>Plane or Train? The Joys and the Burdens</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Scott Tyson letter comments on September 21 editorial urging Congress to enhance Amtrak's ability to ease burden on nation's congested skies and highways by passing High Speed Rail Investment Act before it adjourns; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Speedier Trains'' (editorial, Sept. 21):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Speedier Trains'' (editorial, Sept. 21):</p>
        <p>During nearly 30 years of existence, Amtrak has failed to demonstrate that it can deliver the kind of rail service that would get people off of planes and onto trains.</p>
        <p>Instead of calling for $10 billion in subsidies, you should question whether it even makes sense to continue financing Amtrak at the current levels.</p>
        <p>Why not let the private sector have a chance? If there is indeed a market for high-speed intercity rail travel, then we will have it. With Amtrak's monopoly, all we will ever have outside of the Northeast corridor are passenger trains that are slower than the ones we had 50 years ago.</p>
        <p>SCOTT TYSON  New York, Sept. 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
